    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-13T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-13T19:00:00-05:00" n="1078"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1078">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6363/1–1345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-13T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 13, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>74. Following the request of the National Resources Commission of China we have
                    arranged with the Petroleum Administration for War to send to China two
                    petroleum experts, Martin J. Gavin and Andrew N. Mackenzie, for the purpose of
                    obtaining full data as to what immediate steps might be taken to maintain and
                    expand the production, refining, and distribution facilities of the Kansu Oil
                    Fields so as to achieve the maximum potential supply of oil from this source for
                    war needs in that theatre.<note n="2" xml:id="d1078fn2">The interest of the
                        Chinese Government in the mission was expressed in a letter of December 4,
                        1944, from Dr. C. S. Wang, Director of the Technical Office in the United
                        States of the National Resources Commission of China
                        (893.6363/1–1245).</note> They will leave here about February 1, 1945.
                    Please inform the Chinese Government and the U. S. Military Commander and advise
                    the Department if these arrangements are agreeable. For your guidance the
                    military authorities here have expressed their definite interest in securing
                    this information.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
